1
00:01:38,751 --> 00:01:42,342
This is the Ardèche River
in Southern France.

2
00:01:42,343 --> 00:01:45,116
Less than half of a mile from here

3
00:01:45,117 --> 00:01:51,015
three explorers set out a few days
before Christmas in 1994.

4
00:01:53,161 --> 00:01:55,548
They came along this way.

5
00:01:56,480 --> 00:02:00,371
They were seeking drafts of air
emanating from the ground -

6
00:02:00,372 --> 00:02:03,430
which would point
to the presence of caves.

7
00:02:04,936 --> 00:02:08,221
Eventually they sensed
the subtle airflow

8
00:02:08,222 --> 00:02:10,316
and began clearing away rocks,

9
00:02:10,317 --> 00:02:13,841
revealing a narrow shaft
into the cliff.

10
00:02:14,978 --> 00:02:19,309
It was so narrow that a person
could barely squeeze through it.

11
00:02:20,726 --> 00:02:23,494
They descended into the unknown.

12
00:02:24,395 --> 00:02:27,765
They were about to make
one of the greatest discoveries

13
00:02:27,766 --> 00:02:30,320
in the history of human culture.

14
00:02:39,336 --> 00:02:43,641
At first, the cave did not appear
to contain anything special,

15
00:02:43,742 --> 00:02:47,113
aside from being
particularly beautiful.

16
00:02:54,868 --> 00:02:58,678
But then, deep inside,
they found this.

17
00:03:11,425 --> 00:03:15,593
It would turn out
that this cave was pristine.

18
00:03:15,794 --> 00:03:20,465
It had been perfectly sealed
for tens of thousands of years.

19
00:03:22,364 --> 00:03:28,470
It contained cave paintings
dating back 32,000 years.

20
00:03:29,986 --> 00:03:33,988
In fact, they are the oldest
paintings ever discovered.

21
00:03:34,280 --> 00:03:36,979
More than twice as old
as any other.

22
00:04:16,437 --> 00:04:20,879
In honour of its leading discoverer,
Jean-Marie Chauvet,

23
00:04:20,880 --> 00:04:24,263
the cave now bears
the name Chauvet Cave.

24
00:04:29,332 --> 00:04:33,912
This is road in the Ardèche Gorge,
leading to the cave.

25
00:04:34,853 --> 00:04:36,444
It is early spring.

26
00:04:37,940 --> 00:04:40,369
We've been given
an unprecedented endorsement

27
00:04:40,370 --> 00:04:45,126
by the French Ministry of Culture
to film inside the cave.

28
00:04:47,335 --> 00:04:49,567
From the first day
of its discovery

29
00:04:49,568 --> 00:04:53,367
the importance of the cave
was immediately recognized

30
00:04:53,368 --> 00:04:56,383
and access was shut off categorically.

31
00:04:59,190 --> 00:05:03,026
Only a small group of scientists
is allowed to enter.

32
00:05:03,328 --> 00:05:08,011
They are archaeologists,
art historians, palaeontologists

33
00:05:08,012 --> 00:05:10,871
and geologists among others.

34
00:05:12,280 --> 00:05:15,397
They are here
to perform their studies

35
00:05:15,398 --> 00:05:18,457
during a few short weeks
at the end of March

36
00:05:18,458 --> 00:05:20,543
and the beginning of April.

37
00:05:20,744 --> 00:05:23,538
This is one of the rare times anyone

38
00:05:23,539 --> 00:05:25,865
with the exception of two guards

39
00:05:25,866 --> 00:05:28,170
is allowed inside the cave.

40
00:05:40,618 --> 00:05:44,603
The cave is like a frozen flash
of a moment in time.

41
00:05:46,616 --> 00:05:51,314
The reason for its pristine condition
is this rock face.

42
00:05:51,988 --> 00:05:54,014
Some 20,000 years ago,

43
00:05:54,015 --> 00:05:57,580
it came tumbling down
in a massive rockslide,

44
00:05:57,615 --> 00:06:00,800
sealing off the original
entrance to the cave,

45
00:06:00,801 --> 00:06:03,529
creating a perfect time capsule.

46
00:06:23,272 --> 00:06:27,136
A wooden walkway leads
to the entrance of the cave.

47
00:06:31,680 --> 00:06:35,096
The narrow tunnel,
through which the discoverers crawled,

48
00:06:35,097 --> 00:06:38,994
has been widened and locked
with a massive steel door,

49
00:06:38,995 --> 00:06:41,309
like a bank vault.

50
00:06:44,872 --> 00:06:46,650
Once we pass through this door

51
00:06:46,651 --> 00:06:48,802
it will be locked behind us,

52
00:06:48,803 --> 00:06:53,135
so as not to compromise
the delicate climate inside.

53
00:06:57,295 --> 00:07:00,823
For this first exploration
into the cave,

54
00:07:00,824 --> 00:07:04,958
we are using a tiny,
non-professional camera rig.

55
00:07:08,906 --> 00:07:10,925
In this narrow holding room,

56
00:07:10,926 --> 00:07:14,919
we are fitted with sterile boots
and given safety instructions.

57
00:07:20,311 --> 00:07:21,840
- We have this.
- Good.

58
00:07:21,841 --> 00:07:25,364
Once you've set this on the rock,
you don't touch it.

59
00:07:25,769 --> 00:07:29,258
Clottes was the first scientist
to inspect the cave

60
00:07:29,259 --> 00:07:31,585
a few days after its discovery.

61
00:07:32,180 --> 00:07:34,740
For five years,
until his retirement,

62
00:07:34,741 --> 00:07:37,820
he served as head
of the scientific team.

63
00:07:47,096 --> 00:07:50,418
Our guide leads us down
the first sloping tunnel,

64
00:07:50,419 --> 00:07:54,210
which ends in a vertical drop
to the cave floor.

65
00:09:17,107 --> 00:09:21,013
Since our film crew has been
limited to a maximum of four,

66
00:09:21,014 --> 00:09:24,053
we must all perform
technical tasks.

67
00:09:25,228 --> 00:09:30,343
Our time in the cave
has been severely restricted.

68
00:09:30,806 --> 00:09:32,735
I will take one light as well.

69
00:09:33,587 --> 00:09:35,705
So it's 3.05.

70
00:09:36,321 --> 00:09:38,067
We have one hour.

71
00:09:46,188 --> 00:09:51,382
Apart from time contrictions,
we're not allowed to touch anything.

72
00:09:51,383 --> 00:09:55,164
Or ever step off the
2 ft wide walkway.

73
00:09:59,758 --> 00:10:03,478
We can use only 3 flat
light pannels,

74
00:10:03,513 --> 00:10:05,759
powered by battery belts.

75
00:10:07,871 --> 00:10:13,400
When they made the passageways,
they protected the stalagmites.

76
00:10:17,148 --> 00:10:18,656
It's a nice touch.

77
00:10:20,303 --> 00:10:23,167
Moving along in a single file

78
00:10:23,168 --> 00:10:26,015
the film crew will have no
hiding places

79
00:10:26,016 --> 00:10:28,064
to get out of the shot.

80
00:10:33,567 --> 00:10:36,096
The first large chamber
we come to

81
00:10:36,097 --> 00:10:39,244
is the original entrance
to the cave.

82
00:10:39,716 --> 00:10:42,955
In prehistoric times,
before the rockslide,

83
00:10:42,956 --> 00:10:46,052
daylight must have
illuminated this.

84
00:10:46,519 --> 00:10:49,526
On the left,
right inside the cave,

85
00:10:49,911 --> 00:10:51,713
you could see the entrance.

86
00:10:52,285 --> 00:10:54,944
The archaeological entrance.

87
00:10:54,945 --> 00:10:57,224
People came into the cave, level.

88
00:10:57,058 --> 00:10:59,093
Not like us down a ladder.

89
00:10:59,094 --> 00:11:00,659
The cliff collapsed.

90
00:11:00,929 --> 00:11:03,755
Then we've got
the rubble from the cliff.

91
00:11:05,195 --> 00:11:08,262
From outside you can't see it,
from the inside you can.

92
00:11:11,500 --> 00:11:13,234
Over there you have the dots.

93
00:11:13,935 --> 00:11:15,094
The red dots.

94
00:11:16,955 --> 00:11:20,602
Those are the ones I first saw
when I came to the cave.

95
00:11:21,913 --> 00:11:24,635
Big dots made
with the palm of a hand.

96
00:11:29,260 --> 00:11:32,183
Here we have a big
cave bear skull.

97
00:11:33,858 --> 00:11:35,616
Male, probably.

98
00:11:39,188 --> 00:11:41,308
You'll see many others.

99
00:11:45,614 --> 00:11:49,143
In this big chamber,
which is really huge,

100
00:11:49,144 --> 00:11:50,671
the biggest in the cave,

101
00:11:50,982 --> 00:11:53,950
there are no paintings,
except right at the end.

102
00:11:54,819 --> 00:12:00,644
This is probably relevant.
When the entrance was still open,

103
00:12:00,645 --> 00:12:03,039
there must have been
some light here.

104
00:12:03,404 --> 00:12:06,270
Or they would have been
painting in complete darkness.

105
00:12:16,772 --> 00:12:19,977
This is a cave bear
painted in black.

106
00:12:20,310 --> 00:12:22,182
The paintings look so fresh

107
00:12:22,183 --> 00:12:25,306
that there were initial doubts
about their authenticity.

108
00:12:25,726 --> 00:12:29,664
But this picture has a layer of
calcite and concretions over it

109
00:12:30,127 --> 00:12:32,280
that takes thousands of years to grow.

110
00:12:33,819 --> 00:12:37,309
This was the first proof
that it was not a forgery.

111
00:12:40,333 --> 00:12:44,176
A beautiful horse here,
one of the most beautiful in the cave.

112
00:12:45,681 --> 00:12:51,411
It looks like it could
have been made yesterday.

113
00:12:52,642 --> 00:12:55,797
See how fresh it looks!

114
00:13:01,329 --> 00:13:07,611
Here, behind the horse,
are two mammals. Big mammals.

115
00:13:09,256 --> 00:13:11,786
Here you can see
cave bear scratches.

116
00:13:11,787 --> 00:13:15,070
These scratches do not
have the same colour.

117
00:13:15,071 --> 00:13:19,058
They might have been made
5-10,000 years earlier.

118
00:13:25,335 --> 00:13:28,512
Here's one of the great
spots in the cave,

119
00:13:29,154 --> 00:13:32,096
the famous Panel of the Horses.

120
00:13:33,080 --> 00:13:36,492
It has the size of a small recess

121
00:13:36,493 --> 00:13:41,458
and through that hole there
water comes out,

122
00:13:41,459 --> 00:13:45,615
gurgling after a week of rain.

123
00:13:47,475 --> 00:13:53,382
That may explain why the animals
were painted around that hole.

124
00:13:56,028 --> 00:14:01,246
It's one of the great
works of art in the world.

125
00:14:04,646 --> 00:14:06,912
For these palaeolithic painters,

126
00:14:06,913 --> 00:14:10,407
the play of light and shadows
from their torches

127
00:14:10,408 --> 00:14:13,555
could possibly have looked
something like this.

128
00:14:17,169 --> 00:14:22,361
For them the animals perhaps
appeared moving, living.

129
00:14:23,368 --> 00:14:27,853
We should note that the artist
painted this bison with 8 legs,

130
00:14:27,942 --> 00:14:32,808
suggesting movement,
almost a form of proto-cinema.

131
00:14:44,758 --> 00:14:47,248
The walls themselves
are not flat,

132
00:14:47,584 --> 00:14:50,052
but have their own
three-dimensional dynamic,

133
00:14:50,216 --> 00:14:54,275
their own movement,
which was utilized by the artists.

134
00:14:56,980 --> 00:15:01,303
In the upper left corner is
another multi-legged animal.

135
00:15:01,304 --> 00:15:06,924
The rhino to the right seems also
to have the illusion of movement.

136
00:15:07,800 --> 00:15:10,605
Like frames in an animated film.

137
00:15:23,147 --> 00:15:29,597
The painters speak to us from
a familiar, yet distant universe.

138
00:15:30,716 --> 00:15:35,883
But what we are seeing here
is part of millions of spatial points.

139
00:15:41,268 --> 00:15:46,351
Today, scientists have mapped
every millimetre of the cave,

140
00:15:46,380 --> 00:15:48,508
using laser scanners.

141
00:15:49,405 --> 00:15:53,352
The position of every feature
in the cave is known.

142
00:16:00,118 --> 00:16:03,334
This is the shape of the cave
in its entirety.

143
00:16:04,149 --> 00:16:08,345
From end to end,
it is about 1300 ft long.

144
00:16:10,485 --> 00:16:15,474
This map is the basis
for all scientific projects here.

145
00:16:20,854 --> 00:16:26,922
We are working to create
a new understanding of the cave.

146
00:16:27,139 --> 00:16:31,527
Through precision,
scientific methods.

147
00:16:31,993 --> 00:16:35,915
But that's not the main goal.

148
00:16:36,154 --> 00:16:39,092
The main goal is to create stories

149
00:16:39,281 --> 00:16:43,249
about what could have happened
in that cave in the past.

150
00:16:43,958 --> 00:16:47,504
It is like you're creating
the film directory of Manhattan.

151
00:16:47,616 --> 00:16:53,922
4 million precise entries,
but do they dream or cry at night?

152
00:16:54,259 --> 00:16:57,110
What are their hopes?
What are their families?

153
00:16:57,284 --> 00:16:59,591
You will never know
from the film directory.

154
00:17:00,239 --> 00:17:04,854
We'll definitely never know
because the past is lost.

155
00:17:05,091 --> 00:17:08,001
We will never reconstruct the past.

156
00:17:08,134 --> 00:17:14,212
We can only create a representation
of what exists now, today.

157
00:17:14,577 --> 00:17:17,328
You're a human being,
I'm a human being.

158
00:17:18,010 --> 00:17:22,519
When you come to the cave,
of course there are some things...

159
00:17:22,952 --> 00:17:24,555
I have my own background...

160
00:17:25,326 --> 00:17:26,903
What is your background?

161
00:17:27,262 --> 00:17:31,528
I used to be a circus man,
but switched to archaeology.

162
00:17:31,816 --> 00:17:34,336
Circus? Doing what?
Lion tamer?

163
00:17:34,904 --> 00:17:40,211
Well, not a lion tamer.
Mostly unit cycles and juggling.

164
00:17:41,534 --> 00:17:48,907
When I first entered the cave,
I had a chance to stay five days.

165
00:17:49,914 --> 00:17:55,952
It was so powerful.
Every night I dreamt of lions.

166
00:17:57,082 --> 00:18:00,745
Every day was the same
shock for me.

167
00:18:00,972 --> 00:18:02,461
It was an emotional shock.

168
00:18:02,857 --> 00:18:06,098
I'm a scientist,
and a human too.

169
00:18:06,715 --> 00:18:11,350
After 5 days, I decided
not to go back to the cave.

170
00:18:11,491 --> 00:18:19,911
I needed time to just relax
...and to absorb it.

171
00:18:21,273 --> 00:18:25,011
You dreamt not of paintings of lions,
but of real lions?

172
00:18:25,641 --> 00:18:29,044
Both. Definitely.

173
00:18:29,998 --> 00:18:32,015
And you were afraid
in your dreams?

174
00:18:32,103 --> 00:18:35,696
I was not afraid, no,
it was more...

175
00:18:37,721 --> 00:18:43,091
A feeling of something powerful
and deep.

176
00:18:43,703 --> 00:18:48,074
A way of understanding
that was not direct.

177
00:18:51,800 --> 00:18:55,866
Silence please.
Please don't move.

178
00:18:56,378 --> 00:18:59,075
We're going to listen to
the silence in the cave.

179
00:19:00,113 --> 00:19:03,370
And perhaps we can even
hear our own hearts beat.

180
00:22:29,642 --> 00:22:34,018
These images are memories
of long forgotten dreams.

181
00:22:35,737 --> 00:22:38,939
Is this their heartbeat
or ours?

182
00:22:41,075 --> 00:22:44,972
Will we ever be able to understand
the vision of the artists

183
00:22:45,573 --> 00:22:47,861
across such an abyss of time?

184
00:22:53,033 --> 00:22:56,898
There is an aura of melodrama
in this landscape.

185
00:22:58,874 --> 00:23:01,676
It could be straight
out of a Wagner opera.

186
00:23:01,945 --> 00:23:04,789
Or a painting by
German romanticists.

187
00:23:05,757 --> 00:23:08,517
Could this be our connection
to them?

188
00:23:10,311 --> 00:23:14,015
This staging of the landscape
is an operatic event.

189
00:23:14,512 --> 00:23:17,407
It does not belong
to the romanticists alone.

190
00:23:17,809 --> 00:23:22,372
Stoneage men may have had
a smilar sense of inner landscapes.

191
00:23:22,563 --> 00:23:27,460
It seems natural that there is
a cluster of palaeolithic caves

192
00:23:27,561 --> 00:23:28,740
right around here.

193
00:23:30,090 --> 00:23:33,516
The Chauvet Cave is right here
at the top of this cliff.

194
00:23:33,749 --> 00:23:38,902
The cave is also associated
with this natural feature.

195
00:23:39,096 --> 00:23:41,560
This beautiful arch called Pont d'Arc.

196
00:23:43,021 --> 00:23:47,534
Maybe the Pont d'Arc,
in the mythology of the people,

197
00:23:47,855 --> 00:23:50,285
was not only a landmark,

198
00:23:51,055 --> 00:23:56,858
but a mark in their imagination
and their stories and mythology.

199
00:23:56,859 --> 00:24:00,571
An important way for them
to understand the world.

200
00:24:01,771 --> 00:24:06,460
But what kind of world
was it for palaeolithic people?

201
00:24:06,676 --> 00:24:12,918
35,000 years ago,
Europe was covered by glaciers.

202
00:24:13,264 --> 00:24:18,071
In this glacial Europe,
you must imagine a dry climate.

203
00:24:18,734 --> 00:24:22,809
Cold, but with sun,
that is important.

204
00:24:23,106 --> 00:24:30,192
In this place, you have to
imagine rhinos along the rivers.

205
00:24:30,193 --> 00:24:34,212
In the forest you had
megaloceros deer.

206
00:24:34,389 --> 00:24:40,504
Horses, raindeer, bisons,
and antelopes.

207
00:24:40,889 --> 00:24:42,515
It was very rich.

208
00:24:42,960 --> 00:24:47,347
The biomass in this part of Europe
was very important

209
00:24:47,448 --> 00:24:49,233
for the development of humans,

210
00:24:49,334 --> 00:24:50,739
but also for carnivores.

211
00:24:50,940 --> 00:24:57,870
So imagine lions, bears,
leopards, wolfs, foxes...

212
00:24:57,971 --> 00:24:59,502
in very large numbers.

213
00:25:00,286 --> 00:25:04,169
And among all these carnivores
and predators - humans.

214
00:25:05,619 --> 00:25:08,858
Does the way they set up fires
in the Chauvet Cave

215
00:25:09,044 --> 00:25:12,051
offer evidence that they cast
their own shadows

216
00:25:12,251 --> 00:25:15,419
against the paintings of horses
for example?

217
00:25:15,599 --> 00:25:18,782
The fires were necessary
for looking at the paintings.

218
00:25:19,366 --> 00:25:23,175
And maybe for staging
people around them.

219
00:25:23,331 --> 00:25:28,661
With the flames and moving light
you can imagine people dancing.

220
00:25:30,953 --> 00:25:31,901
Fred Astaire!

221
00:25:32,002 --> 00:25:36,511
The image of him
dancing with his shadows

222
00:25:36,612 --> 00:25:41,743
is a very strong image
of human representation.

223
00:25:42,161 --> 00:25:47,229
A representation of
a white wall and a black shadow.

224
00:26:07,367 --> 00:26:11,601
The presence of humans in the cave
was fleeting like shadows.

225
00:26:13,511 --> 00:26:15,352
Bear skulls everywhere.

226
00:26:16,429 --> 00:26:19,096
These skulls belonged
to the cave bear.

227
00:26:19,459 --> 00:26:23,367
A species like the mammoth
and the wooly rhino

228
00:26:23,368 --> 00:26:26,792
that vanished from
the face of the earth long ago.

229
00:26:36,496 --> 00:26:40,400
Tens of thousands of years
of patient water dripping

230
00:26:40,930 --> 00:26:44,631
has left a thick coating
of calcide on this skull.

231
00:26:45,231 --> 00:26:48,957
It now has the appearance
of a porcelain sculpture.

232
00:27:09,638 --> 00:27:14,921
In all this menagerie of bones,
there's not a single human specimen.

233
00:27:16,504 --> 00:27:21,152
Scientists have determined
that humans never lived in the cave.

234
00:27:21,956 --> 00:27:26,441
They used it only for painting
and possibly for ceremonies.

235
00:27:28,489 --> 00:27:32,899
Michel Philippe has studied
the bones of the Chauvet Cave.

236
00:27:33,789 --> 00:27:39,853
Caves constitute a favourable place
for the preservation of bones.

237
00:27:39,954 --> 00:27:45,971
There are many bear bones,
99 percent of the finds.

238
00:27:46,303 --> 00:27:50,531
There are also some wolves,
two skulls and several bones.

239
00:27:50,728 --> 00:27:52,730
We have a few ibexes

240
00:27:52,831 --> 00:27:55,953
with magnificent skulls
in the wet sand with calcide.

241
00:27:56,013 --> 00:27:56,954
Quite lovely.

242
00:27:58,134 --> 00:28:02,184
When you shine light on it,
calcite crystals glisten.

243
00:28:03,496 --> 00:28:05,595
There are some horses as well.

244
00:28:05,815 --> 00:28:07,723
There's a cave hyena.

