00:45:33,168 --> 00:45:36,771
he has prepared similar figurines
from other regions.

490
00:45:39,142 --> 00:45:44,361
You can see the likeness
in this Willendorf Venus.

491
00:45:45,449 --> 00:45:48,183
It's a copy made in limestone,

492
00:45:48,284 --> 00:45:52,035
found in Austria
from the same period.

493
00:45:52,699 --> 00:45:57,637
In Chauvet, only the lower
part of the belly is preserved.

494
00:45:57,809 --> 00:46:00,045
It's embedded in a bison.

495
00:46:00,289 --> 00:46:03,331
There seems to have existed
a visual convention

496
00:46:03,503 --> 00:46:06,493
extending all the way
beyond Baywatch.

497
00:46:10,078 --> 00:46:13,258
No clear male representation
has been found,

498
00:46:13,259 --> 00:46:20,408
but this lion man comes
from a site in the Swabian Alps.

499
00:46:21,833 --> 00:46:30,107
It's an amazing mixture of
an anthropomorphic shape,

500
00:46:30,476 --> 00:46:33,932
a human body, and the head of a lion.

501
00:46:34,559 --> 00:46:38,138
Is is the spirit
of a lion in a man?

502
00:46:38,581 --> 00:46:42,342
Is it a composed creature,
a new being?

503
00:46:42,559 --> 00:46:46,016
Such equations can be pondered.

504
00:46:51,341 --> 00:46:54,567
What the people who lived
in this valley left behind,

505
00:46:54,740 --> 00:46:56,072
is their great art.

506
00:46:56,394 --> 00:47:00,197
It was not a primitive beginning,
or a slow evolution,

507
00:47:00,421 --> 00:47:04,872
it rather burst onto the scene
like a sudden explosive event.

508
00:47:06,011 --> 00:47:10,005
It is as if the modern
human soul had awakened here.

509
00:47:12,112 --> 00:47:14,570
Even more astonishing
to consider is that

510
00:47:14,371 --> 00:47:18,668
at the time Neanderthal man
still roamed this valley.

511
00:47:21,473 --> 00:47:25,100
But there must have been
other forms of artistic expression,

512
00:47:25,201 --> 00:47:27,040
like music for example.

513
00:47:28,303 --> 00:47:32,161
For this, we had to
look around in nearby regions.

514
00:47:33,256 --> 00:47:37,563
Southwestern Germany
30-40,000 years ago

515
00:47:37,750 --> 00:47:41,298
was connected to this valley
through an icefree corridor.

516
00:47:42,865 --> 00:47:44,515
It should also be noted

517
00:47:44,718 --> 00:47:48,726
that the Alp Mountains
were covered by 9000 ft of ice,

518
00:47:49,028 --> 00:47:50,512
binding so much water

519
00:47:50,659 --> 00:47:54,518
that the sea level was
300 ft lower than today.

520
00:47:56,537 --> 00:47:59,804
A  hunter could have walked
from Paris to London

521
00:48:00,078 --> 00:48:03,294
crossing the dry seabed
of the English Channel.

522
00:48:04,891 --> 00:48:07,589
Walking 400 miles in this direction

523
00:48:07,903 --> 00:48:11,304
woud lead you to the
Swabian Alps in Germany.

524
00:48:14,741 --> 00:48:17,217
In the museum of Blaubeuren,

525
00:48:17,418 --> 00:48:21,662
are replicas of the best-known
palaeolithic Venuses.

526
00:48:35,483 --> 00:48:39,793
But this one, the Venus
of Hohle Fels, stands out.

527
00:48:39,953 --> 00:48:44,483
Found in 2008, it is
sensational for its age.

528
00:48:49,022 --> 00:48:52,464
Venus from Hohle Fels
is probably the oldest depiction

529
00:48:52,733 --> 00:48:56,127
of any kind of figurative object
we know at all.

530
00:48:56,128 --> 00:48:58,921
It's the earliest representation
of a human being,

531
00:48:59,122 --> 00:49:04,449
and it's the absolute root of
figurative depiction as we know it.

532
00:49:04,650 --> 00:49:07,714
Later on, we see a range
of animals being depicted.

533
00:49:07,971 --> 00:49:10,612
The animal depictions
in ivory here.

534
00:49:10,613 --> 00:49:14,127
Or the fabulous depictions
from Grotte Chauvet

535
00:49:14,175 --> 00:49:15,562
of mammoths and lions.

536
00:49:15,785 --> 00:49:17,516
We can see a very clear connection

537
00:49:17,617 --> 00:49:21,416
between the Swabian finds
and the depictions in Chauvet.

538
00:49:21,894 --> 00:49:25,305
It's also fascinating that,
at this time 40,000 years ago,

539
00:49:25,501 --> 00:49:27,592
we see evidence for
musical instruments,

540
00:49:27,693 --> 00:49:29,344
a range of personal ornaments.

541
00:49:29,582 --> 00:49:31,581
Mythical depictions
that clearly show

542
00:49:31,682 --> 00:49:33,986
that these people
had a religious concept

543
00:49:33,987 --> 00:49:37,092
evolving the transformation
between humans and animals.

544
00:49:37,980 --> 00:49:42,550
This is the original statuette
carved from a mammoth tusk.

545
00:49:43,729 --> 00:49:46,612
If we look at the Venus of
Hohle Fels a bit more closely,

546
00:49:46,990 --> 00:49:51,057
we can see very clearly
that the figurine has no head.

547
00:49:51,258 --> 00:49:53,755
Instead of a head,
the figurine has a ring.

548
00:49:53,979 --> 00:49:57,245
It was perhaps worn at times,
suspended on a string.

549
00:49:58,808 --> 00:50:01,091
The sexual attributes are key

550
00:50:01,331 --> 00:50:05,573
which clearly link this depiction
to ideas of reproduction,

551
00:50:05,708 --> 00:50:07,110
fecundity, sexuality.

552
00:50:07,411 --> 00:50:11,381
Ideas that are absolutely essential
to all of humanity.

553
00:50:11,382 --> 00:50:12,526
Also today.

554
00:50:14,210 --> 00:50:16,332
It's also important to realize
that at this time

555
00:50:16,433 --> 00:50:18,964
much of Europe was
occupied by Neanderthals.

556
00:50:19,181 --> 00:50:21,616
We're dealing with the
critical phase in human evolution

557
00:50:21,717 --> 00:50:25,863
where two forms of humans
are testing their boundaries.

558
00:50:26,101 --> 00:50:28,612
What we find,
over and over again,

559
00:50:28,781 --> 00:50:31,206
is that Neanderthals,
although very sophisticated,

560
00:50:31,398 --> 00:50:33,696
never have this kind of
symbolic artefact.

561
00:50:33,697 --> 00:50:34,559
Ever.

562
00:50:37,840 --> 00:50:42,875
This small ivory mammoth was
also found near Hohle Fels Cave.

563
00:50:45,393 --> 00:50:49,586
This beautiful horse
comes from the same rigion.

564
00:50:50,636 --> 00:50:53,271
They also found
fragments of flutes.

565
00:50:53,778 --> 00:50:57,109
We asked Dr Conrad
to show us an original.

566
00:50:57,413 --> 00:51:00,839
The ivory flute
is a remarkable artefact

567
00:51:01,095 --> 00:51:03,845
that Maria Malina discovered
a few years back.

568
00:51:04,180 --> 00:51:08,846
It's extremely important
that we realize that archaeology today

569
00:51:08,935 --> 00:51:12,305
is not a heroic adventure
with spades and picks,

570
00:51:12,740 --> 00:51:16,698
but high-tech scientific work
that's done with indredible detail.

571
00:51:17,164 --> 00:51:19,717
Millimetre by millimetre
the sediments are removed

572
00:51:19,959 --> 00:51:25,537
in these deposits in Chauvet
between 30-40,000 years ago.

573
00:51:25,838 --> 00:51:30,856
This detailed work allowed Maria
to identify a whole range of finds,

574
00:51:30,857 --> 00:51:32,833
which she was able to piece together.

575
00:51:32,884 --> 00:51:34,483
You can explain
how that worked out.

576
00:51:35,376 --> 00:51:38,355
We did an inventory
of all the artefact pieces.

577
00:51:38,356 --> 00:51:41,789
Some of the pieces came
from the 70's,

578
00:51:41,790 --> 00:51:43,659
from the first years of excavation.

579
00:51:44,256 --> 00:51:48,643
They were really small pieces,
which you can see in this picture.

580
00:51:48,922 --> 00:51:54,179
The tiny ivory pieces remained
unexplained for three decades.

581
00:51:54,931 --> 00:52:00,221
31 pieces had a
very significant look.

582
00:52:00,322 --> 00:52:04,125
We found pieces with
a part of the finger holes

583
00:52:04,226 --> 00:52:06,388
and with notches on the side.

584
00:52:06,705 --> 00:52:11,901
I thought that these pieces
could be part of an ivory flute.

585
00:52:12,257 --> 00:52:15,571
An important question was
how the flute was made.

586
00:52:15,772 --> 00:52:23,046
You can see, on the long axis,
a split running along the flute.

587
00:52:23,777 --> 00:52:27,643
Inside the two halfs,
they'd hollowed out the flute.

588
00:52:27,644 --> 00:52:31,990
These little notches along the axis,
along this split,

589
00:52:32,241 --> 00:52:37,390
helped to refit the two halves
together very precisely.

590
00:52:38,006 --> 00:52:44,432
This flute is only one of eight
recovered from SW Germany.

591
00:52:45,299 --> 00:52:47,397
The caves here have no paintings,

592
00:52:47,498 --> 00:52:50,086
but yield many other
objects of art.

593
00:52:50,627 --> 00:52:53,045
In this cave,
the Geissenklösterle Cave,

594
00:52:53,229 --> 00:52:56,580
many important findings
from the Ice Age were made.

595
00:52:57,822 --> 00:53:02,508
We found small ivory statues
of bears and mammoths.

596
00:53:02,509 --> 00:53:04,375
Very tiny mammoths,
very lovely.

597
00:53:04,930 --> 00:53:08,085
In 1992, I was part of
the excavation team.

598
00:53:09,028 --> 00:53:13,716
People lived here
30-40,000 years back in time.

599
00:53:14,325 --> 00:53:16,444
At that time,
it was very cold here,

600
00:53:16,668 --> 00:53:19,047
because the Alp Mountains
were covered by a glacier

601
00:53:19,167 --> 00:53:21,702
about 2500 metres thick.

602
00:53:22,342 --> 00:53:27,160
In the valley down there,
raindeer and mammoths roamed.

603
00:53:27,456 --> 00:53:28,506
It was very cold.

604
00:53:28,507 --> 00:53:31,878
That's why I'm dressed up
like an Inuit.

605
00:53:33,472 --> 00:53:38,786
We presume that Ice Age
people were clothed this way.

606
00:53:39,318 --> 00:53:43,287
In raindeer fur, and in
boots made of raindeer fur

607
00:53:43,543 --> 00:53:44,288
and raindeer leather.

608
00:53:45,457 --> 00:53:48,843
Otherwise you couldn't
stand the cold.

609
00:53:52,482 --> 00:53:54,906
One of the most important finds

610
00:53:55,546 --> 00:53:57,289
we made in this cave

611
00:53:57,507 --> 00:54:01,719
was a tiny flute made
out of the radius of a vulture.

612
00:54:02,973 --> 00:54:08,940
An astonishing fact is
that it's pentatonic.

613
00:54:09,606 --> 00:54:13,726
The same tonality
we're used to hearing today.

614
00:54:15,211 --> 00:54:19,126
If you like, I'll try to
play a tune for you.

615
00:54:36,534 --> 00:54:40,530
I reconstructed the instrument,
tried to play some tunes

616
00:54:40,531 --> 00:54:41,811
and came across this one.

617
00:55:00,670 --> 00:55:03,344
Sounds a bit like
Stars Bangled Banner.

618
00:55:10,426 --> 00:55:12,612
Back in France,
near Chauvet Cave,

619
00:55:13,822 --> 00:55:17,344
explorers using more
primal techniques

620
00:55:17,445 --> 00:55:20,126
in search of still hidden
underground chambers,

621
00:55:20,677 --> 00:55:22,679
roam the landscape.

622
00:55:54,673 --> 00:55:56,475
Professional cave explorers

623
00:55:56,576 --> 00:55:59,796
have techniques for finding
underground chambers.

624
00:56:00,081 --> 00:56:04,043
There are air currents, so they use
the back of their hands

625
00:56:04,482 --> 00:56:07,698
or their cheeks,
to feel for a faint draft of air

626
00:56:07,799 --> 00:56:09,660
that may be coming
out of a cave.

627
00:56:12,457 --> 00:56:14,660
I'm trying to do
things differently.

628
00:56:14,853 --> 00:56:18,812
I have the habit of using
my sense of smell in my profession.

629
00:56:20,816 --> 00:56:25,060
I sniff the smells coming from
the interior of the cave.

630
00:56:28,720 --> 00:56:32,913
Here I couldn't smell anything
except the exterior landscape.

631
00:56:33,619 --> 00:56:37,122
Outside you can smell
the earth, the wild thyme,

632
00:56:37,538 --> 00:56:38,964
the ivy...

633
00:56:39,811 --> 00:56:41,374
You can smell a range of things,

634
00:56:41,553 --> 00:56:43,821
but nothing specific
related to a cavern

635
00:56:44,022 --> 00:56:46,468
that's been closed
for thousands of years.

636
00:56:51,740 --> 00:56:55,702
This is my personal technique,
because I design perfumes.

637
00:56:56,343 --> 00:56:59,327
It's a way to experience it
in a different manner.

638
00:56:59,328 --> 00:57:02,538
I have always created perfumes.

639
00:57:03,529 --> 00:57:08,033
I was the president of the
French society of perfumers

640
00:57:08,034 --> 00:57:09,113
for some years.

641
00:57:34,253 --> 00:57:37,960
There are plans to build
a theme park for tourists

642
00:57:38,089 --> 00:57:42,145
with a precise replica of
the cave a few miles from here.

643
00:57:45,060 --> 00:57:47,304
This replica may even contain

644
00:57:47,305 --> 00:57:51,426
a recreation of the odor
of the prehistoric interior.

645
00:58:14,253 --> 00:58:19,094
Evidently, the odor you can smell
right now is quite attenuated.

646
00:58:19,796 --> 00:58:21,478
It's very subtle.

647
00:58:22,611 --> 00:58:24,637
There are not
many emanations,

648
00:58:24,438 --> 00:58:29,544
but our imagination permits us
to try to reconstruct the scene.

649
00:58:30,823 --> 00:58:34,385
The scene with its odors
from 25,000 years ago

650
00:58:34,553 --> 00:58:37,376
with all the animals
that would have been there.

651
00:58:37,377 --> 00:58:42,808
Bears, wolves, perhaps
even rhinoceroses and men.

652
00:58:43,375 --> 00:58:47,867
The presence of their lives,
meaning burnt wood, resins,

653
00:58:48,099 --> 00:58:51,357
the odors of everything
from the natural world

654
00:58:51,342 --> 00:58:53,390
that surrounds this cave.

655
00:58:53,723 --> 00:58:56,461
We can go back
with our imagination.

656
00:59:04,900 --> 00:59:08,632
With his sense of wonder,
the cave transforms

657
00:59:08,890 --> 00:59:12,096
into an enchanted world
of the imaginary

658
00:59:12,097 --> 00:59:15,131
where time and space
lose their meaning.

659
00:59:17,463 --> 00:59:21,186
These crystal formations
take thousands of years to grow.

660
00:59:22,451 --> 00:59:25,838
The artists of the cave
never even saw them,

661
00:59:25,839 --> 00:59:28,434
as many of them only
started to form

662
00:59:28,605 --> 00:59:31,600
after the landslides sealed
the entrance.

663
00:59:52,488 --> 00:59:55,040
In a forbidden recess of the cave,

664
00:59:55,280 --> 00:59:57,968
there's a footprint of an
8-year-old boy

665
00:59:58,281 --> 01:00:01,012
next to the footprint
of a wolf.

666
01:00:02,814 --> 01:00:05,552
Did a hungry wolf
stalk the boy?

667
01:00:06,203 --> 01:00:08,507
Or did they walk together
as friends?

668
01:00:09,868 --> 01:00:13,311
Or were their tracks
made thousand years apart?

669
01:00:14,358 --> 01:00:15,736
We'll never know.

670
01:01:53,408 --> 01:01:55,857
Dwarfed by these large chambers,

671
01:01:55,955 --> 01:01:58,601
illuminated by all
the wandering lights,

672
01:01:58,934 --> 01:02:03,256
sometimes we were overcome
by a strange, irrational sensation.

673
01:02:03,785 --> 01:02:08,090
As if we were disturbing
the palaeolithic people in their work.

674
01:02:10,232 --> 01:02:12,816
It felt like eyes upon us.

675
01:02:14,512 --> 01:02:18,019
This sensation occured
to some of the scientists,

676
01:02:18,276 --> 01:02:21,094
and also the discoverers
of the cave.

677
01:02:23,180 --> 01:02:26,958
It was a relief
to surface again above ground.

678
01:02:28,577 --> 01:02:32,050
Back outside, we asked
Jean Michel Geneste

679
01:02:32,051 --> 01:02:35,251
about hunting techniques
of palaeolithic people.

680
01:02:35,550 --> 01:02:39,088
Millennia before the invention
of bow and arrow.

681
01:02:39,932 --> 01:02:46,918
The original Chauvet Cave people
had a lots of large game.

682
01:02:46,998 --> 01:02:51,655
They hunted everywhere
in France and Europe.

683
01:02:51,818 --> 01:02:54,796
In their settlements we found
a lot of bones

684
01:02:54,897 --> 01:02:59,647
of reindeer, bison, horses,
and sometimes mammoths.

685
01:02:59,799 --> 01:03:03,588
They had developed
very special hunting techniques.

686
01:03:05,710 --> 01:03:09,873
The original spearpoint system
is very ingenious.

687
01:03:09,874 --> 01:03:12,755
It's a spearpoint on a wooden shaft.

688
01:03:13,806 --> 01:03:20,073
The spearpoint is tied
firmly to the shaft.

689
01:03:20,609 --> 01:03:25,523
The system uses a fork
with a piece inside.

690
01:03:25,676 --> 01:03:27,316
So it's very strong.

691
01:03:27,682 --> 01:03:33,443
It was developed and made
to kill bison or horses like that.

692
01:03:33,768 --> 01:03:37,857
It's very aggressive, strong,
and powerful.

693
01:03:38,181 --> 01:03:44,655
This kind of weapon was
thrown not only by hand,

694
01:03:45,304 --> 01:03:47,312
because it wasn't
very effective.

695
01:03:47,593 --> 01:03:53,603
We suspect that in the beginning
of the Upper Palaeolithic

696
01:03:53,860 --> 01:03:57,149
they developed a
spear throwing technique.

697
01:03:57,623 --> 01:04:05,378
At the tip, the spear thrower
is provided with a hook, a tooth.

698
01:04:05,613 --> 01:04:13,415
The elongated handle
gives the spear a lot of power.

699
01:04:13,416 --> 01:04:19,571
It increases precision
and targeting accuracy.

700
01:04:20,011 --> 01:04:21,531
I will show you.

701
01:04:24,906 --> 01:04:28,348
You see the spear
with the flint point.

702
01:04:28,981 --> 01:04:36,364
There must be a small
depression at the back of the spear.

703
01:04:37,086 --> 01:04:44,953
We suspect they sometimes
used feathers to maintain direction.

704
01:04:44,954 --> 01:04:49,044
I will try to show you
how to kill a horse.

705
01:04:56,361 --> 01:04:59,491
His efforts may not look
very convincing,

706
01:04:59,854 --> 01:05:02,013
but this is a powerful weapon.

707
01:05:02,434 --> 01:05:05,501
Spearheads have been found
deeply embedded

708
01:05:05,602 --> 01:05:08,621
in the shoulder blades
of horses and mammoths.

709
01:05:16,354 --> 01:05:20,167
It flies 30 metres
in a straight line.

710
01:05:23,770 --> 01:05:27,435
The palaeolithic men were
better than you, I guess.

711
01:05:28,019 --> 01:05:34,533
It could be difficult for
me to kill a horse with this.

712
01:05:38,941 --> 01:05:43,345
By mid-April, scientific research
has ended for the year.

713
01:05:43,804 --> 01:05:47,078
Now we are allowed
full access to the cave.

714
01:05:48,601 --> 01:05:53,515
But even that is restricted
to a single week, 4 hrs a day.

715
01:05:54,852 --> 01:05:57,974
The famous cave of Lascaux
had to be shut down,

716
01:05:58,223 --> 01:06:01,043
because the breath
of scores of tourists

717
01:06:01,225 --> 01:06:04,586
has caused mould
to grow on the walls.

718
01:06:11,469 --> 01:06:13,472
We enter Chauvet Cave,

719
01:06:13,573 --> 01:06:17,287
aware that this may be
the only and last opportunity

720
01:06:17,388 --> 01:06:18,961
to film inside.

721
01:07:25,220 --> 01:07:29,525
The mystery of the minotaur
and the female began to unfold

722
01:07:29,589 --> 01:07:32,543
when our guides allowed us
to mount a small camera

723
01:07:32,544 --> 01:07:35,244
on the stick with which
we reached out.

724
01:07:38,631 --> 01:07:42,747
The bison seems to embrace
the sex of a naked woman.

725
01:07:50,323 --> 01:07:54,269
Traditional people, and they think,
people of the Palaeolithic,

726
01:07:54,393 --> 01:08:00,716
probably had two concepts that
changed our view of the world.

727
01:08:01,276 --> 01:08:05,477
The concepts of fluidity
and permeability.

728
01:08:05,621 --> 01:08:09,584
Fluidity means that
the categories we have,

729
01:08:09,616 --> 01:08:15,898
man, woman, horse, tree etc.,
can shift.

730
01:08:16,089 --> 01:08:21,331
A tree can speak, a man can get
transformed into an animal,

731
01:08:21,523 --> 01:08:25,911
and the other way around,
given certain circumstances.

732
01:08:26,122 --> 01:08:29,445
The concept of permeability is

733
01:08:29,772 --> 01:08:34,726
that there are no barriers
between the world where we are

734
01:08:35,095 --> 01:08:36,750
and the world of the spirits.

735
01:08:38,062 --> 01:08:43,929
A wall can talk to us,
or accept us, or refuse us.

736
01:08:45,241 --> 01:08:50,914
A shaman can send his spirit
to the world of the supernatural.

737
01:08:51,071 --> 01:08:57,553
Or he can receive visiting
supernatural spirits.

738
01:08:57,954 --> 01:09:00,629
If you put the two
concepts together,

739
01:09:00,721 --> 01:09:05,552
you realize how different
life must have been

740
01:09:05,685 --> 01:09:07,665
from the way we live now.

741
01:09:11,473 --> 01:09:13,772
Humans have been
described in many ways.

742
01:09:14,580 --> 01:09:20,173
For a while, it was homo sapiens
and it still is homo sapiens,

743
01:09:20,237 --> 01:09:21,838
the man who knows.

744
01:09:22,182 --> 01:09:25,783
I don't think it's
a good definition at all.

745
01:09:25,996 --> 01:09:28,384
We don't know,
we don't know much.

746
01:09:28,659 --> 01:09:34,093
I would say
Homo Spiritualis.

747
01:09:36,005 --> 01:09:38,616
The strongest hint
of something spiritual,

748
01:09:38,703 --> 01:09:41,230
some spiritual ceremony
in the cave,

749
01:09:41,502 --> 01:09:43,173
is this bear skull.

750
01:09:43,739 --> 01:09:46,477
It has been placed
dead center on a rock,

751
01:09:46,636 --> 01:09:48,653
resembling an altar.

752
01:09:50,384 --> 01:09:52,762
The staging seems deliberate.

753
01:09:54,102 --> 01:09:57,113
The skull faces
the entrance of the cave.

754
01:09:57,400 --> 01:10:00,888
Around it fragments
of charcoal were found,

755
01:10:01,270 --> 01:10:03,897
potentially used as incense.

756
01:10:08,814 --> 01:10:13,298
What exactly took place here
only the paintings could tell us.

757
01:13:05,814 --> 01:13:09,377
If you want to have
an understanding of it,

758
01:13:09,478 --> 01:13:12,296
you must go out of the cave.

759
01:13:13,824 --> 01:13:17,498
You must start from the cave
and then go outside.

760
01:13:17,588 --> 01:13:19,782
How far outside?
Where would you go?

761
01:13:20,583 --> 01:13:21,835
I would say everywhere...

762
01:13:23,818 --> 01:13:27,829
A look at the different cultures
would be a good way

763
01:13:28,032 --> 01:13:30,999
to better understand
how different cultures

764
01:13:31,209 --> 01:13:33,481
could have coped with rock art.

765
01:13:34,185 --> 01:13:38,540
In Australia, in North America,
or in South Africa.

766
01:13:38,647 --> 01:13:42,969
Aboriginees in Australia,
who lived until recently

767
01:13:43,184 --> 01:13:45,914
almost like Stoneage people.

768
01:13:45,915 --> 01:13:52,252
They used to paint
and create rock art

769
01:13:52,355 --> 01:13:54,430
until the 1970s.

770
01:13:54,684 --> 01:13:58,662
In some places, I think
there still are traditions

771
01:13:58,663 --> 01:14:00,158
of creating rock art.

772
01:14:00,437 --> 01:14:04,277
Of course, it has changed
since the beginning of the century

773
01:14:04,348 --> 01:14:07,043
when they were discovered.

774
01:14:07,865 --> 01:14:11,486
It can show us different ways
of looking at rock art,

775
01:14:11,487 --> 01:14:14,204
that are not our way
of looking at rock art.

776
01:14:14,345 --> 01:14:16,050
Do you have an example?

777
01:14:16,867 --> 01:14:23,245
In Northern Australia in the 1970s,

778
01:14:23,246 --> 01:14:27,143
an ethnographer was in the field
with an Aboriginee

779
01:14:27,144 --> 01:14:29,121
who was his informer.

780
01:14:29,544 --> 01:14:36,329
Once they came to a rock shelter
that contained beautiful paintings,

781
01:14:36,530 --> 01:14:38,008
but they were decaying.

782
01:14:39,370 --> 01:14:42,100
The Aboriginees became sad

783
01:14:42,101 --> 01:14:44,212
when they saw
the paintings decaying.

784
01:14:44,648 --> 01:14:48,657
In that region, there is a tradition
of touching up the paintings.

785
01:14:49,312 --> 01:14:50,714
Time after time.

786
01:14:51,081 --> 01:14:56,723
So, he sat down and started
to touch up the paintings.

787
01:14:58,699 --> 01:15:06,447
The ethnographer asked the question
all Westerners would ask,

788
01:15:06,639 --> 01:15:07,999
"Why are you painting?"

789
01:15:09,136 --> 01:15:14,426
The man answered,
and his answer was troubling,

790
01:15:14,583 --> 01:15:18,139
because he answered,
"I am not painting."

791
01:15:19,437 --> 01:15:25,336
"It's the hand of a spirit
that is actually painting now."

792
01:15:25,912 --> 01:15:27,465
The hand of a spirit?

793
01:15:28,673 --> 01:15:32,427
The man is a part of the spirit.

794
01:22:50,202 --> 01:22:53,382
Do you think the paintings
in Chauvet Cave

795
01:22:53,383 --> 01:22:57,757
were somehow the beginning
of the modern human soul?

796
01:22:57,908 --> 01:23:00,041
What constitutes humanness?

797
01:23:00,690 --> 01:23:08,765
Humanness is the ability
to adapt to the world.

798
01:23:09,541 --> 01:23:18,057
Man needs to adapt to
the landscape and to other beings,

799
01:23:18,268 --> 01:23:20,829
animals and human groups.

800
01:23:22,887 --> 01:23:25,177
And to communicate.

801
01:23:25,425 --> 01:23:33,363
To communicate by inscribing
memories on specific, odd things

802
01:23:33,761 --> 01:23:37,292
like walls, pieces of wood...

803
01:23:38,741 --> 01:23:42,056
An invention made
by the Cromagnon.

804
01:23:42,244 --> 01:23:43,454
How about music?

805
01:23:44,142 --> 01:23:47,808
Yes, songs, mythology, music.

806
01:23:48,409 --> 01:23:53,287
The invention of the
figurative representation

807
01:23:53,504 --> 01:23:55,298
of animals, of man, of things

808
01:23:55,587 --> 01:24:00,757
is a way for humans
to communicate with the future.

809
01:24:01,781 --> 01:24:05,671
A way of evoking the past
and transmitting information

810
01:24:05,672 --> 01:24:09,063
by means better than language.

811
01:24:09,526 --> 01:24:11,921
Signs instead of
oral communication.

812
01:24:12,498 --> 01:24:18,035
This invention still holds
in our world today.

813
01:24:18,036 --> 01:24:19,933
This camera for example.

814
01:24:45,696 --> 01:24:49,513
On the Rhône River is one
of the largest nuclear power plants

815
01:24:49,514 --> 01:24:50,873
in France.

816
01:24:51,522 --> 01:24:56,158
The Chauvet Cave is located
only 20 miles as the crow flies

817
01:24:56,159 --> 01:24:59,035
beyond these hills
in the background.

818
01:25:00,456 --> 01:25:05,076
A surplus of warm water
that was used to cool these reactors

819
01:25:05,077 --> 01:25:10,128
is diverted half a mile away
to create a tropical biosphere.

820
01:25:11,815 --> 01:25:14,984
Warm steam fills
enormous greenhouses.

821
01:25:15,331 --> 01:25:17,532
And the site is expanding.

822
01:25:38,209 --> 01:25:42,411
Crocodiles have been introduced
into this brooding jungle

823
01:25:42,967 --> 01:25:48,288
and warmed by reactor water,
man, do they thrive!

824
01:25:50,217 --> 01:25:52,267
There are already
hundreds of them.

825
01:26:02,154 --> 01:26:08,269
Not surprisingly, albinos swim
and breathe in these waters.

826
01:26:09,817 --> 01:26:12,738
A thought is born
in this surreal environment.

827
01:26:13,649 --> 01:26:17,945
Not long ago,
a few ten thousand years back,

828
01:26:18,110 --> 01:26:21,523
there were glasiers here,
9000 ft thick.

829
01:26:22,983 --> 01:26:26,377
Now a new climate
is steaming and spreading.

830
01:26:29,903 --> 01:26:33,470
Fairly soon these albinos
might reach Chauvet Cave.

831
01:26:35,114 --> 01:26:39,042
Looking at the paintings,
what will they make of them?

832
01:26:53,943 --> 01:26:57,018
Nothing is real.
Nothing is certain.

833
01:26:58,935 --> 01:27:00,482
It is hard to decide

834
01:27:01,011 --> 01:27:06,001
if these creatures are
dividing into their own doppelgänger.

835
01:27:10,028 --> 01:27:12,702
And do they really meet,

836
01:27:12,703 --> 01:27:16,391
or is it just their own imaginary
mirror reflection?

837
01:27:22,634 --> 01:27:26,727
Are we possibly
the crocodiles who look back

838
01:27:26,728 --> 01:27:28,873
into an abyss of time,

839
01:27:28,947 --> 01:27:31,966
when we see the paintings
of Chauvet Cave?

